<section xml:id="upperlowerbounds">
  <title>Upper and Lower Bounds</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be a nonempty subset of <m>\R</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>A</m> is said to be <term>bounded above</term>
              if there exists <m>M\in\R</m> such that <m>x\leq M</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>.
              Such a number <m>M</m> is called an
              <term>upper bound</term> for <m>A</m>.
              If no upper bound exists, we say <m>A</m> is
              <term>unbounded above</term>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Similarly, <m>A</m> is said to be
              <term>bounded below</term>
              if there exists <m>m\in\R</m> such that <m>x\geq m</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>.
              Such a number <m>m</m> is called a
              <term>lower bound</term> for <m>A</m>.
              If no lower bound exists, we say <m>A</m> is
              <term>unbounded below</term>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              We say <m>A</m> is <term>bounded</term>
              if it is both bounded above and bounded below.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <exercise xml:id="ex_bounded">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that <m>A</m> is bounded if and only if there is <m>t\geq 0</m> so that
        <m>|x|\leq t</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        If <m>A</m> is bounded, there are <m>m,M\in\mathbb{R}</m> so that
        <m>m\leq x\leq M</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>.
        We claim that <m>|x|\leq \max\{|m|,|M|\}</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>.
        Indeed, if <m>x\in A</m> then
        <me>
          x\leq M\leq  |M| \leq \max\{|m|,|M|\}
        </me>,
        and similarly
        <me>
          x\geq m \geq - |m| \geq -\max\{|m|,|M|\}
        </me>
        so that
        <me>
          |x|\leq \max\{|m|,|M|\}
        </me>
        for all <m>x\in A</m>.
        Conversely, if <m>|x|\leq t</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>,
        then <m>-t\leq x\leq t</m> for all <m>x\in A</m>
        (since either <m>x\geq 0</m> in which case <m>x=|x|\leq t</m>,
        or <m>x\leq 0</m>, so <m>x=-|x|\geq -t</m>).
        Thus, <m>-t</m> is a lower bound and <m>t</m> is an upper bound for <m>A</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    Recall that we write intervals using the notation
    <me>
      [a,b]=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; a\leq x\leq b\}, \;\;\; (a,b)=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; a\lt  x\lt  b\}
    </me>,
    <me>
      (a,b]=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; a\lt  x\leq b\}, \;\;\; [a,b)=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; a\leq  x\lt  b\}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    For unbounded intervals, we write
    <me>
      [a,\infty)=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; a\leq x \}, \;\;\; (a,\infty)=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; a\lt  x \}
    </me>,
    <me>
      (-\infty,b]=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\;  x\leq b\}, \;\;\; (-\infty,b)=\{x\in\mathbb{R} \;\; | \;\; x\lt  b\}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <ol label="labelalph">
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>A=[0,3)</m>.
            <m>A</m> is bounded above since <m>3</m> is an upper bound;
            <m>A</m> is bounded below since <m>0</m> is a lower bound.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>A = \{ t+\frac{1}{t}\, :\, t>0\}</m>.
            <m>A</m> is bounded below since <m>0</m> is a lower bound.
            (We could have also shown it was bounded below by using the AM-GM inequality:
            for <m>t>0</m>,
            <me>
              \frac{t+1/t}{2}\geq \sqrt{t\cdot \frac{1}{t}}=1
            </me>,
            so <m>2</m> is also a lower bound for <m>A</m>.)
            But <m>A</m> is not bounded above, since,
            for any <m>M\in\mathbb{R}</m> we can find <m>t>0</m> such that <m>t+\frac{1}{t}\geq M</m>:
            if <m>M \leq 0</m> then any <m>t>0</m> works;
            if <m>M>0</m> then <m>t= M</m> works since
            <m>M+\frac{1}{M}\in A</m> is greater than <m>M</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>A=\{ (-1)^n(1-\frac{1}{n})\, |\, n\in\N\}=\{0,\frac{1}{2},-\frac{2}{3},\frac{3}{4},-\frac{4}{5},\frac{5}{6},\cdots \}</m>.
            <m>A</m> is bounded: 1 is an upper bound since for all <m>n</m>:
            <me>
              (-1)^{n}\left(1-\frac{1}{n}\right)\leq 1-\frac{1}{n}\lt 1
            </me>
            and one can show similarly <m>-1</m> is a lower bound.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>A=\{\sin n\, |\, n\in\N\}=\{ \sin 1,\, \sin 2,\, \sin 3,\, \cdots \}</m>.
            Because <m>-1 \leq \sin x \leq 1</m> for all <m>x</m>,
            <m>A \subseteq [-1,1]</m>, so <m>A</m> is bounded.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>